# File Permissions in Linux

Linux uses a permission system to control who can read, write, or execute files and directories. These permissions help protect system files and user data.

# Types of Permissions

There are three main types of permissions in Linux :

| Permission | Symbol | Meaning |
|-------------|--------|---------|
| Read | r | View file content |
| Write | w | Modify the file |
| Execute | x | Run the file as a program |

# Permission Groups

Permissions are assigned to three groups:

| Group | Description |
|------|-------------|
| User (u) | Owner of the file |
| Group (g) | Users in the same group |
| Others (o) | All other users |

-rwxr-xr-- 1 user user 1200 Mar 5 file.sh

- rwx r-x r--
| |   |   |
| |   |   └── Others
| |   └────── Group
| └────────── User
└──────────── File type

1. chmod : change file permission
      ex : chmod 755 file.sh

2. chmod +x : Add execute permission

3. chmod 755 : set specific permission

4. chown : 
      - Change ownership
      ex : sudo chown user file.txt

5. chgrp (Change Group) :
      - chgrp developers file.txt

     ex : ls -l
          chmod 755 script.sh
          chown user:group script.sh

6. id : 
     - shows group ID, user ID

7. whoami :
     - show current user 

8. groups : 
    - Show group of user




